{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b1d0e017-d067-4a43-825f-24318623fd73","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't check directly. Here's how to diagnose and configure on your target system:\n\n## 1. Determine the Runtime\n\nRun these on your Linux box:\n\n```bash\n# Check if libcoreclr.so is loaded (CoreCLR indicator)\ncat /proc/12345/maps | grep -q libcoreclr && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Likely NativeAOT\"\n\n# Double-check: NativeAOT binaries are fully self-contained, no coreclr\nls -la /proc/12345/exe\nldd \"$(readlink /proc/12345/exe)\" | grep -i coreclr\n```\n\n- **CoreCLR** → `libcoreclr.so` appears in the process memory maps\n- **NativeAOT** → no `libcoreclr.so`; the binary is a single statically-linked (or minimal-deps) native executable\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nSet environment variables (e.g. in your systemd unit or launch script):\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1          # Enable dump on crash\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4            # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t  # %p=PID, %t=timestamp\n```\n\nAlso ensure the dump directory exists:\n```bash\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT doesn't use the CoreCLR dump infrastructure. Use the **OS-level core dump** mechanism instead:\n\n```bash\n# Set core dump pattern\necho \"/tmp/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t\" | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# Remove core file size limit for the process\nulimit -c unlimited   # or in systemd: LimitCORE=infinity\n\n# Ensure dump directory exists\nmkdir -p /tmp/dumps\n```\n\nFor **systemd** services, add to your unit file:\n\n```ini\n[Service]\n# CoreCLR\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4\nEnvironment=DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/tmp/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n\n# NativeAOT (use OS core dumps)\nLimitCORE=infinity\n```\n\n### Analysis tools\n- **CoreCLR dumps** → `dotnet-dump analyze <file>` or `lldb` with SOS\n- **NativeAOT dumps** → `gdb` or `lldb` (standard native debugging; no SOS)\n\nRun the `maps`/`ldd` check first, and the right path will be clear.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bece8dd7-7a22-4071-a887-6f26ee823a96","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345). That's expected since this is a temporary workspace, not the user's actual server. I should guide them through the diagnostic steps rather than trying to run them directly.\n\nLet me provide practical guidance on:\n1. How to determine CoreCLR vs NativeAOT\n2. How to configure crash dumps for each","outputTokens":819,"requestId":"ABC8:24FEAD:1456710:16CEFE8:6A06724D"},"id":"6034c6ed-999b-4216-9dda-b6036f4bde4b","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:09:53.057Z","parentId":"f8788f38-3a7a-4ea9-b089-4945397c9dd7"}
